{
  "answer": "**The matla (opening couplet) of the ghazal in *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 13, warns against superficial perception and urges inner vision.**[^1]\n\nIt states:\n\n> Zahir ki aankh se na tamasha kare koi  \n> Ho dekhna to deeda-e-dil wa kare koi\n\n**Roughly: \"Let no one make a spectacle with the eye of the apparent [*zāhir kī āṅkh*]; if seeing is to be done, let someone open the eye of the heart [*dīda-e-dil*].\"**[^1]\n\nThe claim contrasts exoteric/outward sight (*zāhir kī āṅkh*), which turns reality into mere entertainment (*tamasha*), with esoteric/heart-based sight (*dīda-e-dil*), which grasps deeper truth. This sets the ghazal's Sufi-inspired theme of transcending surface appearances in love and perception.[^1][^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [Chapter 13: \"Zahir ki aankh se na tamasha kare koi\"](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/13-zahir-ki-aankh-se-na-tamasha-kare-koi/transliteration/#p-464c98) (transliteration).\n[^2]: The full ghazal develops this, e.g., referencing Mansur al-Hallaj's mystical execution and Moses at Mount Sinai, but the matla's core claim is this dichotomy of vision.[/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/13-zahir-ki-aankh-se-na-tamasha-kare-koi/transliteration/#p-464c98]",
